---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="Projects">
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="eyebrow">Projects</div>
    <h1>What I'm building</h1>
    <p class="hero-lede">
      A small set of proof-oriented threads, product work, personal systems,
      and infrastructure that show how I think in public. The common thread is
      simple: real AI value appears when runtime, memory, and deployment hold up.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <span class="section-label">Primary threads</span>

    <div class="project" id="sleephub">
      <h3>SleepHub</h3>
      <div class="tag-row">
        <span class="tag">product</span>
        <span class="tag">ambient AI</span>
        <span class="tag">voice agents</span>
        <span class="tag">deployment</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        Ambient, bedside AI product work for autonomous sleep coaching and
        tracking at <a href="https://asleep.ai">Asleep</a>. This is where product,
        device integration, sleep analysis, and real-world user loops meet.
      </p>
      <p>
        It is the clearest public signal of my applied AI work and my bias toward
        systems that have to earn trust over time.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="project" id="knowledge-os">
      <h3>Knowledge OS</h3>
      <div class="tag-row">
        <span class="tag">personal OS</span>
        <span class="tag">markdown-first</span>
        <span class="tag">agent memory</span>
        <span class="tag">public layer</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        A private, agent-native personal operating system built around explicit files.
        Raw sources flow into compiled pages for topics, projects, people, and decisions.
        This public site is one curated output of that system.
      </p>
      <p>
        The pattern matters more than the brand: inspectable memory upstream,
        durable public expression downstream.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="project" id="agent-infra">
      <h3>Agent infrastructure</h3>
      <div class="tag-row">
        <span class="tag">runtime</span>
        <span class="tag">agent control</span>
        <span class="tag">harness engineering</span>
        <span class="tag">workflow</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        Tooling and patterns for making agents reliable enough for real workflows.
        Focus areas include session lifecycle, context packaging, structured control,
        memory continuity, and the interface bridges that make strong systems usable.
      </p>
      <p>
        The interesting problems are what the system does when context is partial,
        state drifts, or humans interrupt. Those are runtime problems.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <span class="section-label">Utilities and experiments</span>
    <div class="project" id="utilities">
      <h3>Open and smaller utility systems</h3>
      <p>
        Practical tools that reduce real workflow friction: deeplink routing,
        automation glue, environment guardrails, and small interaction-layer experiments.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is the scratch-your-own-itch side of my work, but also a real identity signal:
        useful systems over ornamental complexity.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
